VSaaS Hard Gating Workflow
1. CI Pipeline Execution
Pipeline Triggered
A developer commits code, triggering the Lightspeed CI pipeline.
Image Build & VSaaS Scan
The container image is built.
VSaaS scans the image and produces security findings.
Policy Evaluation
The Gating Service retrieves the VSaaS findings and evaluates them against the configured container security policies:
GEMs
Malware
Image Age
Gate Decision
PASS: The image satisfies all configured policies and deployment proceeds.
FAIL: One or more gating policies are violated and deployment is blocked.
2. Remediation Workflow
When a gate fails:
Pipeline Blocked
Deployment to downstream environments is prevented until the gate is satisfied or an approved exception exists.
Review VSaaS Report
The developer reviews the VSaaS HTML report to identify the failing policy and understand the remediation required.
Choose a Resolution
Option A – Remediate
The developer resolves the issue by:
Updating the base image
Removing malware
Resolving GEM findings
Refreshing image age
The changes are committed and the pipeline is re-executed.
Option B – Request Exception
If remediation is not immediately possible (for example, no vendor fix exists or a temporary business exception is required), the developer requests an exception through the existing Lightspeed approval process.
3. Exception Workflow
Exception requests follow the existing approval model.
Development environments: Automatically approved
UAT / Production: Approval required from the appropriate application and security approvers (for example CSI Owner, L3 Head or TISO).
Once approved, deployment can proceed according to the approved exception.
Architecture Notes
VSaaS owns container image scanning and security findings.
Gating Service owns policy evaluation and enforcement decisions.
Lightspeed owns pipeline orchestration, deployment workflow, and exception integration.
Developers consume the VSaaS report to understand and remediate gate failures.
